It's officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe what it's like to fly in a small aircraft, I would say it's like a mix of a motorcycle/quad and a boat 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're immediately very fast. Everything is a bit unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know yet: You steer an airplane on the ground with your feet, not with the control yoke. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's bumpy and you sort of drift. It feels like being in a boat on water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you a bit off course, so you almost have to get used to the motion of the sea, just in the air.
Another random detail:
Flying is physically exhausting. My back and legs hurt today, as if I had been at the gym.
That's not like a Sunday drive in a car. It's more of a sport than a leisurely drive, in my newly gained opinion.
A nice Saturday, my loves. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I'll go again. Then we'll practice stalls and slow flying.
Today the weather was unsettled, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flying and stalls. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph at an airspeed of 65.
It was a nice clear day, a bit misty up higher, but still beautiful.
